<br>
Chapter 2 – Love of a Goddess<br>
<br>
<br>
He was alone..completely alone. His brother’s voices and presence were gone from his mind, leaving a void he never knew existed. He had woken up in a dark, dank cell of stone. The cell was filled with decaying bones, refuse, and a thin layer of molding straw. Some of the bones seemed newer than others; signs that he was not the only recent prisoner this cell had seen. Thick iron shackles held his arms outstretched against the cold, wet surface of a stone wall. Sandalorn had long ago given up trying to keep himself upright and now hung limply from his shackles. He knew not how long he had been down here alone. Time seemed to have no meaning in the black silence of his cell. But since he had not been given anything to eat or drink since he woke, it couldn’t have been more than a few days. He wandered in and out of consciousness as his hunger and thirst kept waking him up from the restless slumber his weakness and exhaustion forced upon him.<br>
<br>
Sandalorn tried not to think of the vast void that now filled his being. His brothers were gone; killed by that creature that called itself The Maestro of Rancor. He never knew just how much the presence of his brothers had meant to him until it was gone. It seemed he was not a whole person anymore, just a dried husk without any inner self-awareness. A tiny mote lost inside the awesome expanse of the universe. He would die down here he knew; cold and alone. His corpse would never lie besides his ancestors; beneath the ground around Tor Anrouk; and thus would never make its journey to the Plane of Growth to be besides his deity. His thoughts turned darker and darker as his life force started to wan and extinguish.<br>
<br>
“Sandalorn….Hear me my faithful” a voice penetrated the soft layer of despair that covered Sandalorn’s mind. “You must not give up hope. You will have a chance to enact revenge upon those who have caused such grief amongst the noble Ellesarien lands. But you must be ready to grab that chance; it comes quickly now.”<br>
<br>
Sandalorn forced himself through the darkness that covered his consciousness. The words had little meaning to him. They were keeping him from the long sleep he deserved. “Go away..Leave me alone to die down here. My brothers are no more. I will join them in awhile.”<br>
<br>
“Sandalorn!” the voice pounded in his head. The power inherent in that voice brought him to full consciousness. “You were not meant to die in this foul place. I have need of you. Your family has served me well since the creation of the of your race, now it is your turn to take up the banner of Tunare and do my bidding upon Norrath” <br>
<br>
“No!” he screamed in the darkness. “I want no more…let me die with my brothers. Let me have peace”. <br>
<br>
“Coward” the voice shattered his thoughts. “Would you have your brothers die in vain? Right now your ancestral home of Tor Anrouk is being overrun by Innoruk’s foul minions and you are busy whimpering in the dark. Would you let your noble family fade into history? Would you abandon your father and mother?”<br>
<br>
“I’m sorry….What can I do down here?” Sandalorn said sorrowfully. “I have not seen or heard anything since my imprisonment. No one is coming to help me..I am alone”<br>
<br>
Suddenly the presence of his loving god Tunare filled his entire being. Exhaustion and pain faded away as energy surged through his frame. “You have never been alone my faithful. I am always here. I will always be here…and I need you my Sandalorn. I need you to be my weapon of vengeance upon the God of Hate.”<br>
<br>
The soft sound of shuffling feet walking upon stone could now be heard faintly in the darkness. “Your chance for escape draws near, young Sandalorn. Are you ready to fight for your life and the life of your family? Are you ready to walk the path of righteousness? To be the hand and sword of your Goddess?”<br>
<br>
Sandalorn wept quietly as the love and blessing of his Goddess washed over him. He could not let her wishes go unheeded. He would fight for her he knew. He would fight until his death darkened his sight and mind. And he would start now! “Yes, my Goddess..I will fight” he whispered. “I will fight for you. Show me how I can be of service”<br>
<br>
“Your chance draws near..be ready” the voice told him. “You must take this jailor without letting him sound an alarm.” The sound of the jailor drew closer until it stopped outside his cell.<br>
<br>
The sound of the cell door being opened broke the thick silence in the dark. It gave a loud creak as it opened to allow a smallish orc to enter carrying a small plate of molding bread and foul smelling water. It sneered at him as it placed the plate on the floor in front of him. Sandalorn did not understand how he was supposed to eat and drink while still being chained to the wall. He assumed that he would be released from his shackles in order to consume the food on the floor. Realization struck hard as the orc jailor spat in his face and then turned around to leave. It never had any intention of letting him eat and drink. It was just another cruel trick to further his torture down in this hellish place. His sight blurred as anger washed over him. They would all pay for this..all of them.<br>
<br>
At the same time the voice rang in his head, saying “Now..Act Now!”, his shackles came free of the wall. Sandalorn fell heavily but the energy and wrath of his Goddess inside his mind forced him quickly back to his feet. The jailor turned at the sound of him hitting the floor…just in time to catch the full force of the thick chain hanging from his shackles across the face. The soft twinkling sound of bone rattled across the stone floor as the jailor’s head exploded in a bloom of red. <br>
<br>
Sandalorn quickly moved to the jailor’s corpse and found a thick set of keys inside the corpses filthy jacket. He thought quickly of trying on some of the foul orc’s clothing, but the thought of wearing anything that these orcs had touched was abhorrent to him. So dressed in only his grimy loincloth, he slowly started to move silently back up the stone hallway that the jailor had traversed. His Goddess’s presence still enveloped him, keeping him full of energy and righteous rage.<br>
<br>
His Goddess’s voice once again penetrated his thoughts. “Not it is up to you my faithful. I will keep you filled with my presence, but I cannot help you anymore than that. You must find your own way out. But I will tell you this; these orcs helped kill your brothers. They were under The Maestro’s command when he killed them.”<br>
<br>
Sandalorn inwardly nodded as he strode through the dark stone hallways. His rage was reaching a head; filling his body with purpose and desire. He wanted to slay all of these foul beings. He wanted to watch their blood run red on the stones.<br>
<br>
After a short while, the air started to freshen and he could hear the sounds of multiple voices echoing down the halls. Sandalorn quickened his pace and soon found himself outside a thick wooden door. The thick, loud voices of orcs behind the door fueled his inner fire as he tried to find the ‘Any’llia’. He slowed his breathing and let his anger and rage disappear as the ‘Any’llia’ washed over him. His thoughts and sight cleared as power and strength coursed through his body. He tested the door and found it unlatched.<br>
<br>
His sudden rush into the room caught the orcs by surprise. His brain registered the room as he burst into the chamber. A crude wooden table sat in the center of the room, chairs of equal craftsmanship surrounding it. A pile of meat and ale filled the table from edge to edge. Apparently the orcs had not feared reprisal and were celebrating their victory. Refuse filled all corners of the room; remnants of meals and other more horrid things piled on one another. Torches along the east and west walls filled the room with smoky light. And across the room, an open door leading to a faint light beckoned him. He also registered the eight orcs that occupied the room; four sitting around the table and the other four lounging lazily on the floor, some even snoring loudly from a drunken stupor. <br>
<br>
All this flashed across his vision as his thick chains swept down upon the closest orc. The wet pop of the orc’s head as it caved in swept over the room and brought Sandalorn to the orcs full attention. Options ran quickly through Sandalorn’s head as he surveyed the remaining seven orcs in front of him. They were spreading out now; crude swords or axes in their hands. He had hoped that his surprise would last longer or that maybe the orcs in their celebration would not have their weapons ready, but that didn’t seem to be the case. Though half drunk, these orcs were battle hardened and had rallied quickly after the initial surprise of his entrance.<br>
<br>
Two orcs suddenly rushed him together, coming around the table from opposite sides. Sandalorn sprinted quickly between them, leaping across the table. His chains slapped across both orcs shoulders as he passed between them. But his situation has worsened. He was now surrounded, standing on the far side of the table. The two orcs he had hit had brushed off the blows by his chains and were now turning to face him on the other side of the table. His options and hopes fading, Sandalorn made a quick fake to one side then moved quickly in the other, catching an orc leaning the wrong way. His right chain splattered the orc’s nose and slapped him back against the wall, which he slid down; stunned. His left chain missed and swung full force against the stone wall. The chain shattered against the wall, breaking off right above his wrist. Now left with only one weapon, he slowly backed himself into a corner, watching the remaining orcs warily.<br>
<br>
Sudden pain from his feet divided his attention briefly as he took a quick glance down. Blood was leaking slowly from a thin gash on the side of his left foot. Sandalorn found the culprit and inhaled deeply. The cold blue tint of Elven Mithril steel poked up through the refuse in this corner. Still staring down the slowly approaching orcs, Sandalorn reached down and brought his hands back up…filled with two ancestral blades of House Ellesarien. Apparently the orcs had just thrown his weapons in the corner of the room until they could be examined later. Food and ale had been foremost in their minds. They would pay for that decision.<br>
<br>
The familiar and comforting feel of his twin blades in his hand brought him into motion. The ‘Any’llia’ settled over him like a warm blanket as he moved from his corner.<br>
<br>
He danced.<br>
<br>
His twin swords were a blue blur as they took out the throat of the closest orc. Pushing the now dead orc back into its companions, Sandalorn now brought the dance of death to them. He blocked the powerful strike of an axe as it arched toward his neck. The loud ring as the two weapons struck echoed inside the small room. Using the axe’s momentum, he pushed it out wide and move inside its arc. His left sword swept the axe owner’s head clean off. The headless body took one step back, pumping blood in the air before it slumped down on the floor with a wet thud. Before the dead body hit the floor, Sandalorn was past and into the remaining orc force. He kneeled down and spun, his sword sweeping back up to gut an orc from groin to chest. Entrails washed down onto the floor as the orc followed his band members into the silence of death. Sandalorn was back on his feet before any of the remaining four orcs could even take advantage of his weakened position. He parried weapon after weapon as he fought to stay in charge of the battle. The four came at him simultaneously; sword following axe in a constant stream of blades. He took a chance and parried with his left as his right flashed over the shoulder of the lead orc and through the throat of the orc behind it. His enchanted blade easily cut through the orc’s flesh and rang against the spinal column as it severed it. His foot lashed out and caught the kneecap of lead orc, bringing it to its knees. The other two orcs, seeing death in this demon of an elf’s eyes, turned tail and fled back up the tunnel. Sandalorn’s swords flashed across the jugular of the kneeling orc as he flowed past him after the fleeing orcs.<br>
<br>
The fleeing orcs heard Sandalorn’s war cry as he chased them down the tunnel. They put their heads down and pumped their legs as quick they could, running for the rays of light a little way ahead of them. The glorious trees of the Emerald Forest could be seen through the entrance. All they needed was to get outside and into the trees; escape was possible then.<br>
<br>
They didn’t make it.<br>
<br>
Sandalorn stood above their steaming corpses as his twin swords dripped blood and gore upon the verdant floor of the forest. He could still feel the blessing and love of his Goddess Tunare coursing through his veins, keeping his energy up even though he hadn’t eaten or drank anything in days. He looked away to the east through the forest..he looked towards home. Not wanting to waste his energy while he had the chance, he started his journey.<br>
<br>
His thoughts were grim as he trod through the forest, thinking about his brothers and what might lie ahead when he found his way back to Tor Anrouk. His rage had settled but still lurked under his calm demeanor. The Maestro of Rancor and his minions had tried to end his and his family’s legacy along with their lives. But he had failed…at least one Ellesarien still lived.<br>
<br>
<br>
To be Cont.<br>
<br>
<br>
