<br>
Chapter Three - Home<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Sandalorn knelt and examined the forest floor. There were signs everywhere for those with the ability to discover them of a mass movement of orcs through the area. It had taken him over two weeks to reach the outskirts of his ancestral home, Tor Anrouk. The thoughts of his Goddess echoed in his memory; “Right now your ancestral home of Tor Anrouk is being overrun by Innoruk’s foul minions and you are busy whimpering in the dark. Would you let your noble family fade into history? Would you abandon your father and mother?” Those words had reached him down in that dank cell where he had been held prisoner and the thought of it had brought up his rage enough to enable him to escape with his Goddess’s help. Since that day, he had moved quickly through the Emerald Forest towards his home, following the path left by the orcs as it wound directly towards Tor Anrouk. He wondered with anxiety what he would find when he finally arrived home. The fear and dread once again started to boil to the surface and he tried to force his thoughts towards the ‘Any’llia’ to calm himself. That of course would never work. You could not force yourself towards the ‘Any’llia’. You had to reach out with love to Tunare; in her the ‘Any’llia’ was found. It took awhile, but soon he was able to balance his thoughts and emotions enough to enter the ‘Any’llia’ and mull over the options that were available to him. He decided to wait here until the cover of nightfall would hide him even more as he approached the tower.<br>
<br>
A few hours later found him at the last ring of trees before the wide clearing that approached the tower. Tor Anouk had certainly been the orcs destination; the small village that surrounded the tower had been utterly destroyed. Bodies of his elven people were scattered everywhere, some in hideous poses left by the orcs for others to find. Circling the tower were stakes adorned with the corpses of elven nobility, including his Ellesarien kin. In the middle, directly in front of the main gate into the tower, stood the stakes where his father and mother were impaled. Sandalorn stared aghast at the pure violence at what had transpired here. The mouths of his parents were stretched wide in a shout of immense pain. Something else besides what was seen had been done to them. His father never would have shown weakness, even in his death. Looking around the clearing, he noticed that all the corpses seemed to have been killed in the midst of a scream. This was a message that needed no seer to explain. It shouted “Those that fight against the might of Innoruk would be utterly destroyed and left as a witness for those that follow”.<br>
<br>
Sandalorn had no knowledge of how long he remained hidden in the trees. His mind simply retreated into itself, looking for a place to hide so he wouldn’t have to come to grips with the loss of his entire life. Finally the continued sight of his parents in their state brought him out of his torpor and fully into rage. Red blinded his vision as thoughts of revenge flashed across his mind. As he stood and started to move towards the stakes, a hand grabbed his shoulder and pulled him back. Even as he twisted hard in the grasp of the person or thing behind him, he cursed himself. How could I have been so stupid? How did I let myself be caught unaware? Even the earliest elven child would not have been caught this way.<br>
<br>
“Steady..Calm yourself young elf” a voice whispered in his ear. Elven! The voice spoke elven, though not of the dialect that the Tor Anrouk elves used.<br>
<br>
Sandalorn let himself relax as the stranger elf turned him around. The elf was no fool though; the grip on Sandalorn did not lessen at all. This stranger was taking no chances and Sandalorn was helpless in his grasp. The stranger’s hands felt like vises as he made sure Sandalorn knew the situation as it stood. As he turned, he finally got a glimpse of his capturer. The stranger was a wood elf alright, having quite a few features in common with the Tor Anrouk elves. His eyes though were a brilliant blue in comparison to Sandalorn’s emerald eyes. He was clad head to toe in forest green chain mail. Etching of ivy leaves wrapped around the armor, making the stranger eerily invisible when looking into the backdrop of the trees behind him. Sandalorn’s mind registered the fact that this elf was most likely wearing the famed Ivy Etched Armor that was whispered in only legends around these parts. His cautiousness and anxiety grew as he wondered now what he had gotten himself into. But he had grown greatly in the past few weeks and would not be cowed by this elf.<br>
<br>
“Who are you trespassing on my lands?” Sandalorn asked intensely. “Have you had anything to do with what happened here? If so elf, your life is forfeit..it is mine to take”<br>
<br>
The strangers eyes grew even grimmer and his grasp became stronger, cutting off the circulation to Sandalorn’s upper arm. “I will forgive you that insult young one because of the loss you have taken. But be warned…One more comment like that and I will leave you here to rot in this forest”.<br>
<br>
The elf stared into Sandalorn’s eyes and took in his appearance. His gaze focused briefly on the twin Ellesarien blades across both shoulders and his grip lessened noticeably. “So..which one are you?”<br>
<br>
“One what?” Sandalorn replied warily.<br>
<br>
“Which Ellesarien are you? By your youth you must be Grefanix or Sandalorn.”<br>
<br>
“How do you know my name? Who are you?” Sandalorn asked quietly. His apprehension was starting to rise again.<br>
<br>
“ My name is not important, but if you must know..it is Andoril. I was a friend of your brother Dannen. We met awhile ago while in the commission of the Felwithe high elves.” He shook his head slowly, his eyes filling with grief. “He became like a brother to me..I am sorry his life has passed. He had much greatness in his future.”<br>
<br>
“You knew Dannen?” Sandalorn said as he searched his memory of many a night sitting around the fire drinking wine, listening to Dannen’s stories that he brought back from Faydwer.<br>
<br>
Suddenly one memory fused into focus. Dannen’s face tightened into a grimace of pain as he recounted night after night battling the Crushbone Orcs in the Greater Faydark Forest. “He saved my life countless times my brothers” Dannen’s words washed upon the shores of his mind. “He is the truest friend I could have…Strong, brave and bold, and reckless in his own life to save yours. If you ever need help and I am not here, go and search for Andoril”. The memory faded as quick as it had arrived.<br>
<br>
Sandalorn twisted out of the now weakened grasp. “Aye..He talked about you. Said we could trust you”. He paused and then finally decided he really had no other choice. “I am the youngest; Sandalorn. I am all that is left. My family is dead”. The sound of those words in the air finally brought home the pain and loss and Sandalorn was soon weeping quietly as he knew he was totally alone.<br>
<br>
Andoril moved quietly back into the trees to let the young elf grieve in privacy. He liked this Ellesarien too. He reminded him much of his brother and Andoril had yet to meet one as noble as Dannen. “Let’s hope that Ellesarien blood runs as deep in this one as his brother. He will need it to survive this”, he thought to himself as he listened to the young Ellesarien letting his grief out. But this was dangerous and they needed to leave quick. He had not found any signs that the orcs were still around, but this felt like a trap to him. <br>
<br>
He coughed quietly as he moved back towards Sandalorn. The young elf had composed himself and now radiated a sense of calm. Andoril smiled to himself even as he could not help feeling a tad jealous. Apparently Sandalorn had found the ‘Any’llia’ that Dannen had talked about so much. He had witnessed countless times the swirling entity of death that Dannen had become when he found that personal calm. He sighed as he thought about all his people had lost in their exodus to Greater Faydark and his elven tree city of Kelethin. They no longer felt Tunare’s presence and the ‘Any’llia’ was just another bit of lost lore that his elders told the youth of Kelethin about.<br>
<br>
His thoughts were interrupted as he spied Sandalorn starting to move out into the clearing. He quickly moved towards the young elf and grabbed his arm again. “I don’t think that is wise young Ellesarien” he spoke quietly. “This feels like a trap to me”<br>
<br>
Sandalorn stopped quickly and perused the surrounding area. “Do you sense anything? I haven’t felt the presence of an orc in a few hours. I think they have left”. He looked back towards his parents and grimaced. “I can’t leave them like that. I need to bury them all. They will not reach Tunare until they return to the earth.”<br>
<br>
Andoril nodded, “I know Sandalorn”. He knew that the young elf would never leave until this task was done. “Let us be quick then”; He moved into the clearing first, his eyes and senses encompassing the surrounding forest.<br>
<br>
He heard Sandalorn following him as he moved towards the elder Ellesariens impaled on the hideous stakes. He drew Wyrmslayer from beneath his cloak and chopped both stakes down by their base. The sound of the two corpses hitting the earth was loud in his ears..too loud. Something was not right here.<br>
<br>
He left Sandalorn to care for his parents as he moved warily around the tower, chopping down the stakes that held the corpses of noble elven blood. His own grief was starting to rise as he thought about the loss here. So many elven dead. So many that they couldn’t afford to lose. Who will strike and hold back the tide that was Innoruk if not the elves? His thoughts raged as he completed his grisly task. Innoruk would pay for this. He would pay in full. <br>
<br>
Sandalorn had completed the burial of his parents. He felt such loss that it was almost overwhelming. At least they would be with Tunare now, helping her in her battle against evil. He rose and went to bury the rest of his people. It would take awhile…there were many corpses. He noticed Andoril watching the trees closely and started to sense the hints of danger. As he moved closer to Andoril, he could see that the Kelethin elf’s hands were white because he was holding his weapon so tightly. Andoril’s weapon itself was a fable….Wyrmslayer…he shook his head in disbelief as he saw legends become reality. This elf must be more than he seemed to be carrying Wyrmslayer and wearing Ivy Etched armor. He planned on finding out.<br>
<br>
Andoril turned as he heard Sandalorn approach. “There is something wrong here here”, he said. “I feel something watching us”<br>
<br>
Sandalorn watched as Andoril’s eyes tightened and focused on something behind him. The Ellesarien elf turned quickly and gasped quietly.<br>
<br>
“Leave this ground vermin” Andoril spoke loudly. “This is elven land and you are not allowed here”<br>
<br>
Stepping out from inside the tower were five elves. But they were not light elves, these were Tier’Dal…Dark elves..Servants of Innoruk himself. They were dressed in chain mail so dark blue it seemed darker than the blackest night. Silver helms covered their faces and each carried two black blades dripping some vile liquid.<br>
<br>
“This is our land now little Fier’Dal” one of the dark elves spat. “We have claimed it in our God’s name”. Suddenly he raised his hands and spoke in his dark tongue. Sandalorn felt a wave of weakness wash over him that almost brought him to his knees.<br>
<br>
He heard Andoril chanting words in Fier’Dal and as quick as it came, the weakness passed. “Beware Sandalorn. These are Innoruk’s favorites..these are his Shadowknights.”<br>
<br>
Andoril was quickly besides the younger elf. Sandalorn looked over and was surprised to see a fierce grin on the Kelethin elf’s face and a dangerous glint to his eyes.<br>
<br>
“Are you ready to strike back, noble Ellesarien” Andoril spoke loudly. “ Here is your first chance”<br>
<br>
Sandalorn found himself grinning also. This crazy elf would be the death of him. Well, he thought to himself, what better way to die then this. He swept his twin swords off his back and looked over quickly, “Aye, Andoril….I am”<br>
<br>
……To be continued…<br>
<br>
Sandalorn Ellesarien<br>
Last Living Heir of House Ellesarien<br>
