<br>
Chapter 4 – Resolve<br>
<br>
<br>
The silence was palpable as the elves stared at each other across the clearing. Sandalorn’s fingers tightened around the hilts of his swords as he took at the pure hate emanating from the Teir’dal’s eyes. The Tier’dal were slowly spreading apart in an attempt to surround the two Fier’dal. They moved with an almost feline grace; their moves slow and measured and they stared down the light elves.<br>
<br>
Andoril whispered to Sandalorn; his eyes never leaving the slowly moving Tier’dal, “We need to act quickly now. If we get surrounded, we are done for. They will expect us to defend or split apart and attack separately. Instead, we will attack together. Get ready and follow my lead young Ellesarien. If we don’t end this quick, they will end it for us.<br>
<br>
With a low growl, Andoril sped across the clearing with incredible pace. He reached a Tier’dal in a few heartbeats and swung his Wyrmslayer in a killing blow. The Shadowknight somehow got his blade up in time to deflect the blow just barely past his neck. But the ferocity of Andoril’s blow had been enough to put the Shadowknight off-balance and he was in a defenseless position for a brief second. He could not get his second blade up in time to stop Sandalorn’s quick swipe across his neck as the other Fier’dal rushed up from the side. The soft whisper of flesh parting heralded the end for the Tier’dal, his throat cut from end to end and leaking his lifeblood upon the ground. He took one more half-hearted swipe at Andoril before his legs gave way and he slumped to the ground, his mail gauntlets coming up to grab at his ruined throat. Wyrmslayer ended all doubt as it swept the Tier’dal’s head clean off.<br>
<br>
The other Shadowknights had acted quickly to the sudden and lightning attack from the two light elves and were in the process of launching a quick counterattack. Three were moving directly towards the Fier’dal in an obvious attempt to simply overpower them. The other held back and drew an evil looking crossbow.<br>
<br>
Without needing words, Andoril and Sandalorn quickly turned back-to-back and moved to keep the three advancing Tier’dal between them and the crossbowman. The Shadowknights took that option away as they charged suddenly and Sandalorn only had a second to witness the crossbowman run to the side to get an unobstructed shot at them before all thoughts were swept away by the force of the Tier’dal charge.<br>
<br>
The elves clashed together with a loud clamor; their swords a blur as they rang off each other. The two Fier’dal were pushed back a few feet on the initial rush of the Shadowknights, but quickly dug their heels in and held their line. Andoril gave a load scream and launched a vicious retaliation; Wyrmslayer slashing across the clean, cool air of the clearing to swipe a Teir’dal’s sword away from it’s owner. The sword went flying across the clearing to land in a puff of dust. Andoril pressed his advantage; sliding up between the widening gap in the Shadowknights line. He beat a flurry of quick, hard blows down upon the now retreating Tier’dal. The Dark elf was defending only now; his one black sword slashing in front in him, trying to keep this devil of a Fier’dal off him.<br>
<br>
Sandalorn tried to keep the other two Shadowknights from helping their weakened ally; his twin swords dancing as he deflected blow after blow. Like Andoril’s target, Sandalorn had no time or energy to launch an attack of any type. He was simply trying to stay alive and was hoping that Andoril would finish off his foe before one of the Tier’dal’s black swords found their way through his whirling defense. He knew it was only a matter of time, as these Shadowknights were fierce and deadly opponents; their years of training with a blade evident in every stroke of their swords.<br>
<br>
Suddenly his wish came true as Andoril’s power and skill finally overcame his opponent and with a lightening attack, he bashed aside the Teir’dal’s lone sword. He reversed his attack and before the Shadowknight could get his sword up in defense, he brutally slashed deep under the Tier’dal armpit. Wyrmslayer cut through links of chain mail and felt backing to sink deep into the Teir’dal’s side. The fatally wounded Shadowknight jerked violently on Wyrmslayer; then slid slowly off the legendary blade and down to the clearing floor, the light in his eyes dimming into night.<br>
<br>
The sharp twang of a loosed crossbow bolt echoed loudly in the clearing. Sandalorn took a quick glance behind him; just in time to see a cruel looking bolt slam into Andoril’s side. The force of the blow dropped Andoril to his knees, blood flowing freely around the bolt now lodged into his side. The Ranger was back on his feet in a second though, his wild cry echoing across the clearing. His hand swept out and ancient Feir’dal words tumbled from his throat. The Teir’dal crossbowman suddenly burst into flame, his night black hair quickly sparking and catching fire. The flaming Tier’dal did not panic though. He was his God’s faithful; his wrath upon this land. He uttered words in the vile language of the Tier’dal and as quickly as it came, the flames extinquished. He brought his crossbow back up to fire, only to see it charred and useless from the flames that had spread down to it. Throwing the crossbow to the ground, the Dark elf drew an ugly looking flail; its ends dripping the same vile liquid that flowed across his companion’s blades.<br>
<br>
Andoril could feel the poison of the crossbow bolt starting to flow through his system, slowing movement and thought as it raced through his bloodstream. His vision was starting to fade and lose clarity. He could see the burned Tier’dal move slowly towards him, his flail making a whirling sound as he whipped it around over his head. The Dark elf seemed to be taking his time, confident in the fast acting poison that he knew was quickly shutting down the Fier’dal system. He would rue his sloth.<br>
<br>
Sandalorn was quickly tiring, his energy fading in the constant battle against the two remaining Tier’dal swordsmen. Andoril’s soft cry of pain almost cost him his life as he turned to take another quick glance at his fellow Fier’dal. Andoril was weaving gently on his feet; his hands pressed hard against the wound in his side. But he had not dropped Wymslayer and looked to be preparing to return blows to the slowly advancing burned Tier’dal. A loud whir of a blade barely missing his throat brought Sandalorn’s attention fully back to his fight. He barely had time to get both his blades up in time to catch a furious attack by one of the Shadowknights. He cursed at himself for loosing concentration and re-doubled his efforts, his arms burning with fatigue as he brought the battle to the Tier’dal swordsman. All he needed was to get them off balance for just a second. He charged directly at one of the Shadowknights, his swords flashing in the morning sun as he pushed the Tier’dal back. He used the brief opening to slip between the two dark elves and slide behind them. Drawing a throwing dagger, he threw himself into a low roll and came up throwing in one long languid motion; the dagger rushing across the clearing to sink deep into the throat of the flail carrying Tier’dal. The Shadowknight took two more steps forward before his brain registered the fact that his lifeblood was flowing down his neck and onto his black chain mail. He finally ground to a halt, his eyes wide with surprise and fear as he crumpled to the ground, joining his fellow Shadowknights into darkness. Andoril slumped down besides the slain Teir’dal, Wyrmslayer falling softly out of his hands. The poison had finally started to slow and stop his functions.<br>
<br>
Even being as quick as he was, Sandalorn had left himself badly undefended by the two remaining Shadowknights. Without looking behind him, he threw himself into another roll, coming back up facing the Tier’dal. But he was not fast enough to stop one of the swordsmen from slashing deeply across his left wrist. His Ellesarien blade dropped from nerveless fingers as he lost feeling in his left arm. Sandalorn knew he was in deep trouble. Blood was flowing freely from the wound on his left wrist, slowly draining the energy and fire from the Fier’dal. Now left with only one sword, he knew he could not defeat both these Shadowknights. He had to do something drastic soon or all was lost. Feigning defeat he knelt on the ground, his hand reaching inside his Elven cloak. The remaining two Shadowknights grinned evilly at each other and strode forward, ready to end this battle.<br>
<br>
Sandalorn quickly drew another dagger and stabbed it as hard as he could through the leather boot of the nearest Shadowknight. The dagger pierced the tough leather easily, piercing deep into soft flesh to come rattling to a stop against bone. The Tier’dal halted and lost his concentration and focus in the pain rushing from his damaged foot. That was all the time Sandalorn needed as he came to his feet quickly; his sword following him to jerk up through the hurt Shadowknight’s groin to lodge deep in his abdomen. He tried to withdraw the blade, but the Shadowknight had twisted as he fell to the clearing floor, trapping Sandalorn’s blade and ripping it from his hand.<br>
<br>
Sandalorn only had time to turn and look as the remaining Shadowknight, glee gleaming in his twisted eyes, brought his sword up to make the final killing blow. He knew he was doomed, his life forfeit. He gave a quiet prayer to Tunare to watch his soul.<br>
<br>
Thwaaap…The sound of an arrow being released was barely recognized before the triple edged point suddenly appeared from the remaining Shadowknight’s mouth. Sandalorn watched as the Tier’dal grin was replaced by immense pain. He was staring directly into the Shadowknight’s eyes as the light winked out in them.<br>
<br>
The young Ellesarien looked behind the dying Tier’dal to see Andoril crumple to the ground, his bow grasped tightly in his hand. Even in his state of fatigue and exhaustion, Sandalorn’s mind registered the workmanship of the Elven bow. “Raincaller” he said softly to himself, shaking his head. This Felwithe elf was a warehouse to the unbelievable.<br>
<br>
Wrapping his wounded wrist and retrieving his twin swords, Sandalorn wearily walked across the clearing to his hurt comrade.<br>
<br>
To be continued……<br>
